home.subtitle1: Discover, monitor, and integrate public APIs.
home.subtitle2: Your mission control for the API universe.
home.readyPrompt: Ready to find your next API?
home.feature1Desc: Search and filter through 1800+ public APIs. Find the perfect API for your project in seconds.
home.feature2Desc: Real-time health checks and uptime tracking. Know if an API is alive before you integrate.
home.feature3Desc: OpenAPI specs, interactive docs, and code examples. Everything you need to get started fast.
home.feature4Desc: AI-powered summaries and use case suggestions. Understand any API at a glance.
home.step1Desc: Search, filter, and discover APIs by category
home.step3Desc: Find APIs that work without authentication
home.faq1Answer: Public API Navigator is a production-grade directory that syncs with the public-apis repository, adds real-time health monitoring, and provides structured metadata to help developers discover and evaluate public APIs without guesswork.
home.faq2Question: How do I use this platform?
home.faq2Answer: Browse the catalog, use filters to narrow down APIs by category, authentication type, CORS support, or health status. Click any API to view detailed information, health metrics, and interactive documentation.
home.faq3Question: Are all APIs free to use?
home.faq3Answer: Most APIs in the catalog are free for basic usage, but each provider sets their own terms. Check the individual API documentation for pricing, rate limits, and authentication requirements before integration.
home.faq4Answer: ApiNavigatorBot performs hourly health checks on API homepages (not endpoints) with SSRF guards and rate limiting. Status pills show real-time availability: green (online), yellow (slow), red (down), or gray (not checked).
home.faq5Answer: APIs support various auth methods including No Auth, API Key, OAuth, JWT, and more. Use the auth filter to find APIs that match your security requirements. Each API page displays the specific auth type needed.
home.faq6Question: Can I add my API to the catalog?
home.faq6Answer: This platform syncs with the public-apis/public-apis GitHub repository. To add your API, submit a pull request to that repository following their contribution guidelines. Your API will appear here after the next sync.
home.faq7Answer: CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) determines if you can call the API directly from browser JavaScript. 'Yes' means browser-friendly; 'No' or 'Unknown' means you need a backend proxy to avoid CORS errors.
home.faq8Answer: The catalog syncs with the upstream repository regularly. Health checks run hourly with timestamps visible on each API page. The 'Last Checked' field shows exactly how recent the status information is.
home.useCase1Desc: Find no-auth APIs to build MVPs and demos without complex authentication setup
home.useCase2Desc: Verify API health and uptime before committing to production dependencies
home.useCase3Desc: Compare multiple providers in the same category to find the best fit for your project
home.useCase4Desc: Discover APIs for teaching programming concepts and building student projects

api.fieldGuideIntro: You want to ship {name} without surprises. These steps keep things safe and reproducible, based on lessons from running APIs in production.
api.fieldGuideStep1: Read the auth badge. If it says "No", you can demo fast. If it says "apiKey" or "OAuth", plan key storage.
api.fieldGuideStep2: Check HTTPS. If false, route through your own HTTPS gateway before user data ever touches it.
api.fieldGuideStep3: Look at CORS. "Yes" means you can call from the browser. Anything else: use your backend proxy.
api.fieldGuideStep4: Scan the latency and uptime. Under 400ms and green pill? Go ahead. Slower or red? Add cache and a fallback.
api.fieldGuideStep5: Copy the curl button, hit the homepage, and watch logs. Trust but verify.
api.fieldGuideNote: Use the auth, HTTPS, CORS, status, and latency signals above to decide if this provider is ready for production or needs a cache/fallback plan first.
api.checklistItem1: Set request timeouts (start with 5s). Physics beats optimism.
api.checklistItem2: Use exponential backoff and circuit breakers; never DDoS a provider during an outage.
api.checklistItem3: Log request IDs and status codes. Future-you will thank present-you.
api.checklistItem4: Cache GET responses when allowed; cut latency and protect rate limits.
api.checklistItem5: Document the key scopes and expiry so teammates are never locked out.
api.checklistItem6: If health is yellow/red, design a graceful fallback: hide the widget or serve stale-but-honest data.
api.actionAuth: Match your secret handling and least-privilege scopes.
api.actionCors: Browser direct or proxy? Decide now.
api.actionHttps: If "No", terminate TLS at your edge.
api.actionLastChecked: Freshness tells you if the signal is hot or stale.
api.signalsNote: Data source: public-apis list plus live health checks. Checks probe the homepage URL only, with SSRF guards and polite pacing. Timestamps tell you exactly how fresh the signal is.
api.whatIsDesc: In one line: {description}. In human terms: this sits in the {category} lane, and it wants you to solve {useCase} without wrestling docs. If you can explain it to a fifth grader, you can ship it. Example: "{name} lets us do {description}"--that is your elevator pitch.
api.whenToUse: Best times to use it: when you need a drop-in service for the category above and you value quick adoption over custom-building. Times to skip it: if you require hard SLA guarantees and the status pill is yellow/red, or if HTTPS is false and you cannot front it with your own TLS.
api.handsOnStep1: Open the homepage link above. Confirm docs and auth instructions match what you see here.
api.handsOnStep2: Run the copy-paste curl: curl -I {link} to verify reachability from your edge.
api.handsOnStep3: If auth is {auth}, create a least-privilege key and store it in your secrets manager.
api.handsOnStep4: Prototype one happy-path call in the playground below. If OpenAPI is present, the "Try it" UI will render automatically.
api.handsOnStep5: Set timeouts and log request IDs in your code. Ship a small canary before full rollout.
api.evidenceItem1: Upstream listing: public-apis/public-apis, a large community-maintained catalog with constant churn.
api.evidenceItem2: Health stats above are measured by ApiNavigatorBot with SSRF guards, timeouts, redirect caps, and HTTPS validation.
api.evidenceItem3: OpenAPI (when present) is normalized to absolute URLs so "Try it" works without guessing domains.
api.evidenceItem4: Last checked timestamp shows freshness; if old, treat status as advisory and retest manually.

about.title: cat README.md
about.subtitle: About Public API
about.missionP1: Public API Navigator is a production-grade directory for public APIs. It keeps the famous public-apis list in sync, adds live health checks, normalizes OpenAPI docs, and serves a browser-safe playground so teams can evaluate providers without guesswork.
about.missionP2: The goal is E-E-A-T by design: experience from running real systems, expertise encoded as filters and guardrails, authoritativeness through transparent sources, and trustworthiness via timestamps, status pills, and OpenAPI links you can verify yourself.
about.feature1: Structured metadata for thousands of public APIs: auth, CORS, HTTPS, category, source repo.
about.feature2: Live health signals (status, latency, last checked) with hourly probes and clear timestamps.
about.feature3: OpenAPI discovery and normalization so Swagger UI renders without guessing servers.
about.feature4: SSRF-protected playground with copy-ready curl/fetch/Python/Axios snippets.
about.feature5: Sitemap, robots, and JSON-LD for strong SEO; canonical URLs for every API detail page.
about.pipeline1: Sync upstream: pull the public-apis repository and normalize entries with deterministic IDs.
about.pipeline2: Enrich: fetch OpenAPI docs when available; capture source repo metadata for traceability.
about.pipeline3: Probe: ApiNavigatorBot pings only homepage URLs with TLS validation, redirect caps, size limits, and an SSRF guard.
about.pipeline4: Store: write summaries (status, latency, last checked, errors) to the catalog with typed payload schemas.
about.pipeline5: Serve: Next.js app exposes search, filters, health timelines, and JSON-LD for each API.
about.security1: SSRF guard blocks private/reserved IP ranges, enforces protocol allowlist, and caps redirects + body size.
about.security2: Probes are lightweight (homepage only), staggered through the day, and identify with a fixed user agent.
about.security3: No cookies or auth headers are sent; playground proxy is rate-limited and host-allowlisted per API.
about.security4: Cache headers enable CDN edge caching while keeping health signals fresh.
about.security5: Every page links back to the original source so you can independently verify data.
about.statsStarsWhy: Community scrutiny keeps the source list honest.
about.statsForksWhy: Thousands of maintainers patch and extend entries.
about.statsLastUpdateWhy: Shows the upstream list is alive, not frozen.
about.statsOpenApiWhy: Swagger UI renders reliably without guessing hosts.
about.statsNote: Source repo: public-apis/public-apis. Numbers above refresh automatically; if GitHub is unreachable we display conservative defaults.

bot.title: ./ApiNavigatorBot
bot.subtitle: Health check bot powering status pills and latency metrics
bot.infoP1: ApiNavigatorBot runs the health checks that power the status pills and latency numbers you see across the catalog. It is designed to be polite, transparent, and safe by default.
bot.infoP2: The upstream source is the public-apis repository ({stars} stars, last updated {updated}). Checks are layered on top so you get fresh signals without stressing providers.
bot.userAgentNote: This user agent is fixed so you can spot me in logs or blocklist/allowlist as you like. I respect robots spirit, rate limits, and human requests.
bot.flightPlan1: Pick target: I only touch the homepage URL listed in the catalog, not hidden endpoints.
bot.flightPlan2: Resolve safely: DNS lookups are validated to avoid private or loopback ranges.
bot.flightPlan3: Connect with guardrails: HTTP/S only, TLS validated, redirects capped.
bot.flightPlan4: Measure pulse: Record status code, total time, and a small byte sample to ensure content exists.
bot.flightPlan5: Store and display: I post the result into the health timeline you see as green/yellow/red pills.
bot.flightPlan6: Back off: Batches are staggered through the day to avoid thundering herds.
bot.flightPlanNote: The goal is a trustworthy heartbeat, not a load test. Think of it as tapping the spacecraft hull---not firing the main engines.
bot.security1: Only http/https protocols are allowed---no ftp, ws, custom schemes.
bot.security2: Private, local, and reserved IPs are blocked to prevent SSRF.
bot.security3: Redirect targets are re-validated to stay out of private networks.
bot.security4: Response size caps keep memory sane and respect upstream bandwidth.
bot.security5: Timeouts prevent zombie connections; failures degrade gracefully.
bot.security6: No cookies, no auth headers, no scraping of page data---just liveness and latency.
bot.statusPillDesc: Green = homepage responded within guardrails. Yellow = slow but alive. Red = unreachable. Unknown = not checked yet.
bot.latencyDesc: Milliseconds from request start to response headers. Under 400ms feels snappy worldwide; over 1s means plan a cache.
bot.lastCheckedDesc: Timestamp in local time so you know how fresh the pulse is. Fresh beats fancy.
bot.statsSourceListWhy: Large, active community keeps entries current.
bot.statsLastUpstreamWhy: Shows the list is actively maintained.
bot.statsProtectedWhy: SSRF guard rejects private or reserved ranges.
bot.statsDataCapturedWhy: No scraping; just enough to show liveness.
bot.contactP1: See the user agent above? Add a contact header or email in your response and we will read it. If you need the bot to slow down or skip your domain, reach out via the project GitHub issues.
bot.contactP2: If you want to collaborate on better health signals (like region-aware probes or authenticated checks), open an issue. Builders helping builders is how this catalog stays sharp.
bot.faqQ1: Does the bot hit real API endpoints?
bot.faqA1: No. Only the public homepage URL is pinged. No auth, no data harvesting.
bot.faqA2: Traffic is tiny, spaced out, and respects timeouts. It is designed to be lighter than a human page view.
bot.faqA3: Trust grows when the lights are on. You deserve to know what is touching your servers.
bot.faqA4: Open an issue, drop evidence, and I will rerun, fix, and document. Fast feedback keeps the signal clean.
